# burst worked example (manual/circuits/burst.md): a trigger starts `count`
# pulses at frequency `hz`, 50% duty (gate width = half the period). Here at
# tickrate 8 with hz=1 the period is P = tickRate/hz = 8 ticks, so each pulse is
# 4 ticks high + 4 ticks low; count=3 gives three pulses back to back.
#
# Phase convention (SPEC-GAP, analogous to lfo): the first pulse is emitted on
# the trigger tick itself (phase 0 at the trigger tick), then phase advances by
# 1/P per tick. High iff floor(phase) in [skip, skip+count-1] and frac<0.5.
# Trigger rises at t1, so burst-relative tick k = t-1; phase = k/8.
#   k 0..3   -> phase<0.5 in cycle 0 -> HIGH   (t1..t4)   pulse 1
#   k 4..7   -> phase>=0.5           -> LOW    (t5..t8)
#   k 8..11  -> cycle 1, frac<0.5    -> HIGH   (t9..t12)  pulse 2
#   k 12..15 ->                       -> LOW    (t13..t16)
#   k 16..19 -> cycle 2, frac<0.5    -> HIGH   (t17..t20) pulse 3
#   k >=20   -> floor>=3 out of range-> LOW    (t21..)    burst done
tickrate 8
patch <<<
[burst]
    trigger = I1
    hz      = 1
    count   = 3
    output  = O1
>>>
@0 expect O1 0
@1 set I1 1
@1 expect O1 1
@2 set I1 0
@2 expect O1 1
@3 expect O1 1
@4 expect O1 1
@5 expect O1 0
@6 expect O1 0
@7 expect O1 0
@8 expect O1 0
@9 expect O1 1
@10 expect O1 1
@11 expect O1 1
@12 expect O1 1
@13 expect O1 0
@14 expect O1 0
@15 expect O1 0
@16 expect O1 0
@17 expect O1 1
@18 expect O1 1
@19 expect O1 1
@20 expect O1 1
@21 expect O1 0
@22 expect O1 0
